How to Finance the Green Transition
New York – This week, world leaders gathered in New York at the United Nations to assess the global war on climate change and submit new pledges for emission reductions.
The climate crisis demands urgent action, and our pace of doing things is far from enough.
We are lagging in accelerating our actions.
Accelerating the pace of change requires collaborative efforts from both public and private sectors.
Fortunately, private sector collaboration to combat climate change is increasing thanks to the work of the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI).
Under the leadership of Michael Bloomberg, the UN Special Envoy for Climate Action, the Climate Finance Leadership Initiative (CFLI) was established with the aim of mobilizing global private capital to address this critical issue.
This month, CFLI released a new report titled "Financing the Low Carbon Future," outlining how to expand green finance to support a smooth low-carbon economic transition and presenting opportunities for public-private cooperation to achieve the Paris Climate Agreement goals set in 2015.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) is the largest multilateral investor in climate-related projects worldwide.
But now, responding to the call of the leaders of European countries and the newly elected President of the European Commission Ursula von der Leyen, we are prepared to step up EIB's role as a specialized climate bank for the EU.
The EIB will mainstream climate considerations, targeting low-carbon investments, and commit to investing at least 1 trillion euros in low-carbon projects over the next decade.
To achieve this goal, at least 50% of the EIB financing will be directed towards climate action and environmental sustainability by 2025.
By the end of 2020, we will align all our financing activities with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement.
As an important first step, we will exclude energy projects reliant on fossil fuels.
Additionally, we will position the EIB as a green finance incubator, committed to mobilizing other resources to assist economies in transitioning to a low-carbon future.
As an EU bank, our task is to invest in Europe's future, and the most pressing issue among them is undoubtedly climate change.
How urgent the climate crisis is, the stronger our resolve will be.
This summer, Europe suffered from record-high temperatures and crop failures due to last year's drought.
Many developing countries have had similar experiences.
Floods and other climate-induced phenomena impose billions of dollars in annual costs on major cities, threatening even more lives.
But the climate crisis also presents an opportunity, as funding new green infrastructure can create jobs, stimulate economic growth, and reduce air pollution that plagues major cities around the world.
Shifting investment models could accelerate the transition away from fossil fuels. This transition has already begun.
Market forces are increasingly favoring clean energy over fossil fuels.
In 2011, half of America's coal-fired power plants were retired, while the clean energy sector created 3.3 million jobs, compared to fewer than 100,000 in the coal industry.
Moreover, an increasing number of American cities and states have committed to achieving net-zero emissions by 2050.
They will receive support from Beyond Carbon, a program initiated last year by the Bloomberg Philanthropies aimed at achieving full decarbonization of the US economy.
As part of the international community, we must not only invest in clean energy but also reduce investments in dirty energy.
Currently, in terms of fossil fuel subsidies, we are essentially spending money to promote climate change and air pollution.
These funds should be directed towards引导 investment in electric vehicles and other technologies that can drive the green transition.
These investments will yield significant returns, including reducing the substantial costs to public health caused by air pollution.
Additionally, we can take numerous measures to steer the necessary funds.
First, we must improve data and disclosure standards.
For a long time, businesses and investors have been unaware of climate-related risks, unsure of the rationale for reducing carbon emissions or protecting assets from extreme weather impacts.
This is beginning to change.
The recommendations of the Task Force on Climate-related Financial Disclosures are guiding businesses to allocate capital in more sustainable ways, allowing investors to reward companies that seriously address climate change.
Next, we must clarify investment risks associated with green finance.
Cities account for more than 70% of CO2 emissions, but only a few developing world cities have access to credit ratings.
As a result, the total investment in clean public transportation, energy-efficient buildings, and other emission-reduction projects has been affected.
Governments and listed banks must step up efforts to help cities attract capital for these projects, including through initiatives such as the Global Covenant of Mayors for Climate & Energy, which is supported by the EIB and co-led by Bloomberg Philanthropies.
Third, we need to modernize the power grid.
Incentives such as refunds and tax breaks have promoted the expansion of wind and solar power, reducing costs for both businesses and consumers.
Now, we should introduce similar programs to accelerate the deployment of battery storage and other emerging technologies to overcome intermittency issues.
Furthermore, better grid connectivity can enable regions with excess wind and solar power to supply areas with insufficient power.
Governments can play a leadership role in encouraging more private investment in clean power.
Finally, we must continue to expand the green investment market.
In 2007, the EIB issued the world's first green bond on the Luxembourg Stock Exchange, and since then, the green bond market has grown to $136 billion.
But compared to the $100 trillion global bond market, this is merely a drop in the bucket.
Therefore, the EIB is helping to develop sustainable finance standard classifications for the EU so that investors can compare similar projects, much like with standard bonds.
More detailed information about carbon footprints can empower investors to make informed decisions, thereby directing more private investment towards low-carbon projects.
This is how we finance the green transition.
